@node help "ignition - How To Use This Guide"
 @{b}1.1. Usage Of This Guide@{ub}

The context sensitive help will be triggered by the "help"-key on your keyboard; ignition will try to open a meaningful entry about what's currently placed under your mouse cursor.
In the sheet itself, ignition will also differentiate between all user interface elements, while it usually only has one help entry for one window.
An exception to this rule are the windows using tabs; you will find a help entry for every single tab in this guide.

The entries are linked throughout the document. Sometimes, you'll find buttons to trigger actions in the application itself. If an entry have buttons for this, you'll generally find them at the end of it, separated by a short line.
This functionality is implemented using ARexx, since ignition can be completely controlled remotely. However, this guide is not generated on demand, so it assumes that ignition is accessible using the "ignition.1" port name - but this is not guaranteed, in case you've opened ignition more than once at a time. In this case, the action may be triggered in another running ignition, or even not at all.

The position of the help window on the screen can also be saved: choose the (lonely) item "Save As Defaults" in the "Preferences" menu.

@endnode


@node cell_input "ignition - Text- and Formula Input"
 @{b}1.2. How To Enter Cell Texts And Formulas@{ub}

The first difference in comparison to other spread sheet applications you'll notice is probably when you want to overwrite an existing cell text with something else; if you just start typing in a cell, the old text is not deleted, but it can be edited, any new letters will just be added to this one. Depending on the configuration, you can even just press the "Shift" key to enter the cell text editing mode.

ignition differentiates between texts, values, and formulas for text input:

@{b}Text:@{ub} Everything that doesn't match one of the defined
   format templates is considered to be text.
   If you prepend the input with '#', it's always considered to
   be text, even if it would match a format template.
   If the text starts with a number (and not with '#'), it will
   adopt this as its value for calculations. For example, the
   entry "23 cars" has the value 23, although there is no format
   template that fits.

@{b}Values:@{ub} Every input will be matched against the existing
   @{"format templates" link format}. Hence, the value of the entered
   text is determined by the format: for example, "0:42" can be
   parsed as 42 minutes, but also as 42 seconds, depending on the
   existing formats and their order (which can be changed by assigning
   priorities to them). Valid inputs as recognized by the standard
   formats are i.e. "Monday", or just "23".
   
   Every value is of one of the following types:
	 Value	 - the value of the input is adopted directly
	 Percent - value in percent
	 Date	 - in days
	 Time	 - in seconds
	 Unit	 - Values with a unit

   These types can be mixed arbitrarily in formulas, although the the
   base unit is not respected in this case, i.e. "1s" + "Monday" is
   not Monday, 0:00:01 but valueof(Monday) + valueof(1s) which is 2
   in this case.
   To separate fractions, either "." or "," will be accepted (because
   of national differences).

@{b}Formulas:@{ub} If the input line starts with a '=', it is interpreted
	as a formula.
	ignition knows about the following operators than can be used in
	calculations:
     + - * /  - basic arithmetic operations
	 :        - range between cells (i.e. a3:a5)
     !        - factorial
     > >= < <=
     = !=     - comparisons
	 & | ~    - bit-wise relations: and, or, not
	 && ||    - logical relations
     %        - modulo
     ^        - power

   Case is insensitive for functions, names, etc. You can auto complete
   a function name, name, or database using the tab key. Press the key
   again to browse through all possibilities.

   Besides operators and numbers (the exponential notation is not yet
   recognized), you can use the following operands:

   @{b}Strings@{ub}
   To identify a string as string (and not as a name), you have to use
   quotes. You cannot use all operations on strings, and you also cannot
   mix text and numbers in calculations.
   Example: "Hello "

   @{b}Cell References@{ub}
   If a name consisting of characters only ends with a digit, it will
   be recognized as a reference to another cell. The character references
   a column, the number references a row, i.e. "a4" references the cell
   in column "a" (the first one), row 4.
   These references are relative to the current cell; if you copy it
   somewhere else, the reference will change to the cell with the same
   distance. If you want to reference an absolute cell position, you
   can do so using the "$" (dollar) sign before the column or row
   identifier, e.g. "$a$4".
   You can also specify ranges of cells using the ':' colon. If a
   function doesn't expect a range for this argument, or if you are
   using the range in a normal formula, it stands for the sum of
   the range; hence, "=summe(a3:a6)" is the same as "=a3:a6".

   Using '#' you specify a reference to a cell or range of cells on
   another page or map; after the first '#' you can either put the
   name of the page or its page number. Between the cell reference
   and the page identifier is another '#' as in: "#Page 2#a4".
   Note, the page reference is absolute; if you insert pages or
   rename existing pages, they won't get updated, and you won't
   be warned about existing references.
   Examples: a2, $b3, $t$42, #Page 2#a4, #2#b3, #2#a4:#2#b6

   @{b}Functions@{ub}
   If there is an opening parenthesis after a alphanumeric string,
   it is recognized as function.
   You can get a list with a short description of all functions
   when you click on the @{"Choose..." link window_formula} button in the project window.

   @{b}Names & Databases@{ub}
   You can access the fields of a database using the '.' "operator"
   (for example, persons.name, or persons.2 for the 2nd field).
   If a name substitutes with a range, you can use the same mechanism
   there as well.
   Cell references in names are always absolute; you don't need to
   specify the "$" sign for them. If you need relative cell references
   in names, you can use the reference() function.

@endnode


@node interactive_mode "ignition - Interactive Mode"
 @{b}1.3. Interactive Mode@{ub}

ignition has two different modes it can be in:

 · In the ordinary edit mode you have all the power to change
   the cells, and you can change and add masks and buttons - but
   they don't have any function; events are not handled.

 · During the interactive mode, you can use buttons and similar
   user interface elements in the sheet, as well as database
   masks.
   Events handlers that the author of the document has installed
   will be called.
   However, you cannot select more than one cell at once, or any
   other object in the document.

The right corner of the help bar indicates the currently active mode; it will either show a "inter" for the interactive mode, or a "edit" for the editing mode.
See also: @{" Help Bar " link helpbar}, or @{" Icon Bar " link iconbar}; the latter contains a button to switch the modes in the default configuration.

Please note that the interactive mode can be disabled when the document is loaded for the first time, even if it has been saved in the interactive mode. This is a security feature that lets you open documents from unknown or unsave sources without having to worry.
Known documents are remembered in the session file.

