@node drag&drop "ignition - Drag & Drop"
 @{b}1.4. Drag & Drop@{ub}

The process of grabbing an object, dragging it over another, and drop it there to trigger a certain action is generally called "Drag&Drop".
It can be used at several places throughout ignition's user interface. Almost all list fields support this method of interaction; in the preferences window for the icon bar there even is no other way to drag existing commands into the bar.

It's important to know that ignition supports both scrolling with a selected entry and drag&drop at the same time: if you select an entry and move the mouse below while holding the mouse button down, you won't drag that entry around but just select the next entry in the list which may come in as a surprise.
If you really intend to drag an entry, you have two choices: you can move the mouse a bit horizontally with a pressed mouse button, or you hold down the "Alt" key when you select the entry - of course, you still have to keep the mouse button pressed in this case, but you can release the "Alt" key immediately after the drag has started.
In both cases, you will now drag the entry over the screen and can be dropped over another object by releasing the mouse button.
Usually, the target object gives you a visual hint to indicate acceptance, for example, its frame changes to a black and white dashed line.
@endnode

 
@node beginner "ignition - Beginner-Mode"
 @{b}1.5. The "Beginner"-Mode@{ub}

ignition has a beginner mode which becomes active automatically, if you select "Beginner" for the installation.
The beginner mode hides some preferences modules from the user to make the settings less confusing and easier to use. The following preferences are not editable in this mode:

 · Commands
#ifndef IGNITION_LITE_EDITION
 · Menu
 · Context-Menu
#endif
 · Keyboard
		
Additionally, several System preferences item are hidden as well.
The beginner mode is set via ToolTypes - the setting is stored in the program icon of ignition. To deactivate the beginner mode, just put the ToolType "BEGINNER" in parentheses as in "(BEGINNER)".
@endnode


#ifdef IGNITION_LITE_EDITION
@node full_version "ignition - Differences To The Standard Edition"
 @{b}1.6. Differences To The Standard Edition@{ub}

This is the "Lite Edition" of ignition. In contrast to the "Standard Edition", the following restrictions have been introduced:

 · no interactive Mode; sheets cannot have buttons, internal scripts or similar
 · no database functionality
 · the menu preferences are not available
 · some graphical add-ons are missing
 · the Turbocalc Import-Filter is missing
 · the maximum sheet size has been restricted to 30 x 50 cells (not limited in the Standard Edition)
 · the ARexx port is cut down to the bare minimum (open, save, new, close, print, & quit)

As owner of the SuperBundle, you have the possibility to upgrade to the "Standard Edition" for a reduced pricing. Please contact your local dealer to get more information on that subject.
@endnode
#endif


